# Datasheet for MetaGesture-30K

Following the framework of Gebru et al., "Datasheets for Datasets"
(Commun. ACM, 2021).

## Motivation

**For what purpose was the dataset created?**
To fine-tune the gesture modality encoder (Temporal Convolutional Network,
Section 4.1 of the paper) of the MEIA Multimodal Perception Module on
naturalistic skeletal motion data captured during metaverse interactions.

**Who created the dataset?**
Collected by the MEIA research team under institutional ethics approval
**#IRB-2024-0147** (same approval covering MetaConvo-50K).

## Composition

**What do the instances represent?**
Each instance is a 53-joint skeletal pose sequence captured at 60 Hz
during a single interaction session.

**How many instances?**
30,000 motion-capture sequences.

**Does the dataset contain all possible instances or a sample?**
A sample, collected in-lab from 48 individual volunteers (the same
participant pool used for MetaConvo-50K text collection), across multiple
sessions per participant.

**What data does each instance consist of?**
53-joint 3D skeletal coordinates at 60 Hz, session metadata (scenario
type, duration), no audio or video recording.

## Collection Process

**How was the data collected?**
Collected in a motion-capture laboratory using a marker-based optical
tracking system, from 48 volunteers who gave informed consent for
research use, as described in Section 4.1 of the paper.

**Who was involved in the collection process?**
Research staff under IRB-2024-0147 supervision.

## Preprocessing/Cleaning/Labeling

Raw marker trajectories were converted to a standard 53-joint skeleton
format, temporally synchronised to the 60 Hz capture rate, and
quality-checked to remove tracking dropouts exceeding 200 ms.

## Uses

**Has the dataset been used for any tasks already?**
Yes — fine-tuning the TCN gesture encoder (8 layers, 128-dim) for gesture
category classification as part of Stage 1 pre-training (Section 4.4).

## Distribution

**Will the dataset be distributed to third parties?**
**Raw motion-capture sequences are NOT publicly redistributed.** Consistent
with the consent protocol under which participants were enrolled (research
use by the original collecting institution only).

**What is released instead?**
1. This datasheet (full collection and consent protocol)
2. Derived 128-dimensional gesture embeddings (post-TCN, pre-projection)
3. The fine-tuned TCN encoder checkpoint (see `checkpoints/`)

## Maintenance

**Who maintains the dataset?**
The corresponding author of the paper. Contact via GitHub Issues for
questions about data provenance.

## Ethical Considerations

Collected under IRB-2024-0147 with informed consent from all 48
participants. Motion-capture data of this kind can in principle be used
for biometric re-identification; access to raw sequences is restricted to
the original research team for this reason, consistent with the consent
participants provided.
